messages.content:
Hey folks,

I'm super glad to be here & e-meet y'all.

Normally, I stay pretty stealth about this in anything remotely professional, but I'm trans. Nice to meet more LGBTQ+ folks in tech
@AFunkyMonkey Hi, I was just wondering what is it like being trans in modern day? What can cisgendered people do to help you?

Hi @gallop ,

Thanks for asking. I'm not quite sure how to answer that in any way that's deeper than surface level concepts that just boil down to being respectful decent human beings.

I.e. asking for someone's pronouns rather than assuming,...

I'd be happy to chat more via DMs.

Ok, and as I sent that, I remembered something.

Not sure how other places do this, but at Apple (yes, I'm guilty of selling my soul to the corporate overlords of the Silicon Valley), our internal directory application & web interface have a spot right below our names for pronouns. So mine would say she,her,hers & have a ? Icon that pops up to explain when to use each (which in turn is great for people with limited English too).

We're also allowed to use preferred names for all correspondence, internal directory, and yadayada, which is great for trans folk who haven't yet had a legal name change.

Advocating for these is always awesome!
i think that we should start asking gender pronouns to new people and be cool with being asked at the same time 👀

I’m also cis but I have heard rhetoric about trans people being worried about passing, like for example Nikita dragun has done a CRAZY amount of invasive procedures to look more feminine (she even got facial reconstruction surgery where they shave off parts of your bones iirc). I’m seeing a gender fluid person and she had an experience with a homophobe with a guy friend where someone called her a faggot in public but it made her happy because she was feeling super masc that day and it meant she passed

My understanding is that gender dsyphoria is mostly a personal experience though, meaning that trans people who want to change their bodies do it so they can have the body they feel like they should’ve from the start instead of so people can see them as what they actually are. It’s super interesting I’d love to hear from trans people who can talk about their experiences because I’m not super educated

Thanks for your reply Ciara, I was concerned I touched a nerve / was insensitive towards what I’m sure is a difficult topic for some.

I’d like to hear more perspectives, as a straight white male in arizona I really only have the privilege of hearing other straight/lgbtq white people and often asking questions isn’t something I’ve felt comfortable doing, whether that’s our culture here or my approach to conversation, I can’t say. Just trying to learn and understand so I can live from a place of empathy 😌
Sounds kinda dope if I identified as a woman and then a cute guy hits on me, fat W

@bigfacts  I think the conversation about passing is more nuanced too. Like many people talk about violence towards non-passing trans people and it’s at the intersection of a lot of identity points of race, socio-economic status and normalized beauty standards. There is disproportionate amount of violence towards black trans womxn vs any other race within America. On the flip side of trans men, I find that mainstream media does not cover as much or celebrates it differently. I.e. Eliot Page coming out last week as a trans male and all the hype and commotion vs. Laverne Cox being attacked with her friends when out in LA that happened just a few days before Eliot’s announcement. There’s room for both for discussion, but what is talked about more? 🤔

On a side note, I have seen some tech companies be more progressive on hiring from trans communities as technical employees. Before this past decade, many trans communities either had to be extremely discreet/hidden which is where passing is a touchy subject, but most go tos have been service / hospitality / sex work. My trans roommate a while back was a sex worker / barista until they were able to learn programming and landed a fellowship at IBM to start their career in tech. They’re now about to graduate the fellowship and move on into their first job that isn’t minimum wage being almost 32 after transitioning around 22. Especially when a role becomes merit and knowledge based, in theory this is how tech could be more accessible on paper but culture is also a main driver away for diverse communities to be apart of the picture.

Just throwing in my $0.02, it does feel pretty great to be stealth & not have people know you're trans. Ultimately, no one knows your situation like you do, but pride events often occur around areas that are really popular to begin with. If staying in the closet is the route you go (and don't let anyone kick you down for it 💜), you could always go with the "Oh I wasn't at Pride, I was really craving XYZ place's coffee, sushi,........."

I'm part of a volunteer event medic service that does the SF pride parade & etc, so if I wanted to hide my being trans, a hoodie or shirt with the logo of the service could go a long with pretending that I was just a medic "healing the sick"(or drunk, more likely).

Not sure where you are or what you're planning on doing after school, but there are tons of groups of peeps that are totally great about helping you protect your privacy while still being who you are. Some companies have great employee groups for it (i.e. Pride@Apple, Pride@Facebook,...)

Hey so I realize this may not be the most appropriare place for this kind of posting, but I figured since people like us are at a much higher risk for it, some of you might be interested.

I recently started as a Director building out a Technology Operations Center (TOC), Security Operations Center (SOC), & running the partnership program for a non-profit that provides technical & cyber-physical support to folks who are escaping or have escaped & need help to stay free from Domestic Violence, Stalking, Harassment, & all the related crimes where your sense of safety & sanctity as a person are being plagued with fear.

It's all unpaid volunteer work, but it makes for great resume fodder, you get to help real people make huge changes in their lives for the better, free access to a lot of quality training (OSINT/CTI, DFIR, OPSEC,...), & pretty great network of powerful folks in tech. Also super duper flexible, since we all do this in addition to our day jobs & other commitments like side work, school, family,...

We're currently looking for:
TOC Software Engineers : yes, you code monkeys! Churning out code to help build out internal tools
TOC Engineering Manager: person to oversee the above. Great for people who are ICs/TCs in their day job but want to get some program / project management experience while doing something important.
TOC Support Specialists: Folks who'll roll their sleeves up & see what they can do to fix the tech problems that come their way. Everything from a shelter's staff member saying they can't print to potentially migrating on-prem resources to public / private cloud,.... you never know.
TOC Operations Manager: Manager for the above. Also great for people who are ICs/TCs in their day job but want to get some program / project management experience while doing something important.

SOC Analyst: Great for both entry-level & experienced security folks. Deal with escalations from the TOC when they come across an indicator of compromise like a shelter staff member calling in a panic because someone's remotely accessing their machines & stealing confidential data for people in the safehouse. Or train non-technical audiences to avoid being socially engineered. Or.... anything else.

If this sounds interesting to you or if you'd like to learn more, please feel free to DM me.
